<h1>
Bibletime Development&nbsp; - Setting up access to the CVS repository</h1>

<h2>
Checking out sources,</h2>
Open a shell terminal, cd to the directory where you want the cvs tree
to be copied, then:
<h3>
To check out the bibletime source,</h3>
For anonymous access use the following commands to login:
<br>cvs -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs.bibletime.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/bibletime
login
<br>#simply press return at the password prompt
<br>cvs -z3 -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs.bibletime.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/bibletime
co bibletime
<br>If you are a developer, export CVS_RSH=ssh
<br>cvs -z3 -d:ext:developername@cvs.bibletime.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/bibletime
co bibletime
<h3>
Checking out sword sources</h3>
Bibletime depends on the sword back end. For anonymous access use the following
commands to login:
<br>export CVSROOT=:pserver:anonymous@cvs.crosswire.org:/usr/local/cvsroot
<br>cvs login
<br>Password: anonymous
<br>cvs -z5 checkout sword
<br>If you are a developer and want to work with the sword source, Please
contact scribe@crosswire.org
<h2>
Command line customization</h2>
Setting up the most common cvs command lines as defaults.&nbsp; More information
can be found in the info documentation for cvs.
<p>If you access the bibletime cvs repository often you will want to set
up some command line default options.
<br>Create the file $HOME/.cvsrc
<br>In a text editor add the lines:
<br>cvs -z4 -q
<br>diff -u3 -p
<br>update -dP
<br>Now when you type cvs the command cvs -z4 will always be used.
<br>&nbsp;
<h2>
Setting up GUI cvs interface.</h2>
The cvs graphical user interface may be useful if you access the repository
<br>often. There are two that have been tested with the sourceforge
<br>repository.&nbsp; These are the setup instructions.
<br>&nbsp;
<h3>
cervisia</h3>
First you need to read the sourceforge site documents CVS HOWTO and the
CVS_SSH FAQ,
<br>and set up the .ssh directory with authorized keys and known hosts.&nbsp;
The
<br>handbook in the cervisia package has good information also.
<p>Start cervisia from the K menu bar.
<br>Under the repository tab in the 'configure access to repositories'
dialog box
<br>click the add button enter on the repositories line
<br>:ext:username@cvs.bibletime.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/bibletime
<br>enter on the remote shell line
<br>ssh
<br>Close the add dialog box and the 'configure access to repositories'
dialog box
<br>Try an update command on your existing bibletime repository.&nbsp;
It should complete without errors.
<h3>
Caution</h3>
The checkout feature does not seem to work on all installations, however
if a
<br>copy of the bibletime CVS is downloaded using the command line options,
cervisia
<br>will work just fine.
<br>&nbsp;
<br>&nbsp;

